Handing someone else your money doesn’t mean it goes to that person tax-free. The IRS considers all Corp-to-Corp transfers a net accession to wealth and it would be taxed. Corporations can’t “gift” anything, money or otherwise, without it being a taxable event (that includes plane rides, t-shirt’s, you name it). So, if Kim’s company got $600M, then Kim’s company would pay tax on 100% of it and she’d have to disclose where it came from. Handing someone else your money doesn’t mean it goes to that person tax-free. The IRS considers all Corp-to-Corp transfers a net accession to wealth and it would be taxed. Corporations can’t “gift” anything, money or otherwise, without it being a taxable event (that includes plane rides, t-shirt’s, you name it). So, if Kim’s company got $600M, then Kim’s company would pay tax on 100% of it and she’d have to disclose where it came from.
